For several days, the new world epidemic of pneumonia continued to spread, so that investors in the United States and Europe to see the approaching of the Black Swan.

Local time February 25, U.S. stocks suffered another heavy loss. Dow Jones Industrial Average closed down 879.40, or 3.15 percent, at 27,081.36 after dropping more than 1,000 points on Feb. 24, while the S & P 500 index closed down 97.70, or 3.03 percent, at 3,128.21, down 6.3 percent in two sessions, the Nasdaq ended down 255.70 points, or 2.77 percent, at 8,965.61.

China's Shanghai and Shenzhen a shares in overseas markets in the context of a continuous slump, but also failed to remain immune. The Shanghai Composite Index fell 0.83 per cent for the day to 2,987.93 points on February 26, before falling below the 3,000-point psychological barrier again. The Shenzhen Composite Index fell 3.02 per cent to 11,497.55. The previously strong a-share index fell 4.66 per cent to 2,180.70 on February 26.

Morgan, an unnamed economist at Chase, told Caijing that time was running out for irrational exuberance to dominate the market. U.S. stocks have fallen for three straight days, starting with the Feb. 21 sell-off and the Nasdaq's biggest one-day percentage decline in about three weeks. Market sentiment has changed, if not completely reversed, at least to wait and see.

While new cases continue to increase in Asia, the Middle East and Europe, there has been a sharp increase in new cases reported in Iran, Italy and South Korea. Major European indexes Tuesday closed down, with Italy's FTSE MIB down 1.44% , FRANCE'S CAC 40 down 1.94% , Germany's DAX down 1.88% and Britain's FTSE 100 down 1.94% . International oil prices continue to fall. Tuesday closed 3 percent lower at $49.90 a barrel for West Texas intermediate and 2.4 percent lower at $54.95 a barrel for Brent Crude. International gold prices also weakened sharply, the market profit-taking signs are obvious. Tuesday closed the day with April gold, the most traded commodity on the New York Mercantile Exchange, down $26.60, or 1.59 percent, to $1,650 an ounce.

The risk to the American public remains low, but it is likely to change rapidly as the epidemic spreads globally, said Alex Azar, Secretary of Health and Human Services, in a Feb. 25 press conference.

Earlier in the day, Nancy Messonnier, director of the CDC's National Center for Immunization and respiratory disease, also said at a media briefing that sooner or later the new coronavirus would spread in the United States. "The question is not whether it will happen, but when it will happen and how many people in this country will become seriously ill, " she said, adding a warning: "The disruption to daily life can be severe. "

There are currently 57 confirmed cases of new coronavirus infection in the United States, mainly in evacuees, including evacuees from the Diamond Princess cruise ship in Yokohama, Japan, and evacuees from Wuhan. Of the 14 confirmed cases in the United States, 12 had a history of travel to China and two had close contact with people with travel histories.

The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and prevention also warned on the same day that if the new coronavirus spreads widely in the United States, it will mean that a large number of people will need medical care at the same time, this will impact many aspects of society, such as medical care, schools, transportation, law enforcement, emergency response, etc. .

Jeffrey Young, former global head of foreign exchange at Citigroup and co-founder and CEO of Deepmacro, told Caijing that the continued spread of the virus outside China could worsen market sentiment. The CDC's warning is important because if the outbreak leads to tighter travel restrictions, it could have a more serious negative impact on the economy.

The mayor of San Francisco, Bridger, declared a state of emergency on Friday amid fears of a new outbreak of pneumonia. While San Francisco has no confirmed cases, Bridger said in a statement, "the global situation is changing rapidly and we need to step up our preparedness. ".

U.S. stocks fall at crossroads

For the past decade, the U. S. stock market has been a bargain-hunting operation. Since the last bear market, the S & P 500 has fallen 5 per cent or more on 25 occasions, each of which has been a buying opportunity. The stock market has been rocked by a downgrade of the US credit rating, a trade war, Brexit and the 2011 earthquake in Japan.

It was a bargain-hunting exercise that was supposed to be repeated on February 25th. After "black Monday" , the three major indexes of U. S. stocks all opened higher on Tuesday, it seems to come a wave of rebound operation. But U.S. stocks quickly turned lower in a panic that sent the Dow to its lowest level since October 2019 and sent the S & P 500 down another 3 percent, to more than 7.6 percent for the fourth day in a row.

"The U.S. economy is now in its 11th year of expansion, " said Robert Barbera, director of the Center for Financial Economics at Johns Hopkins University. "everything that scares you in the last 11 years, in hindsight, is a buying opportunity. "

Following the same line of thinking at a time when U.S. stocks are being sold off again, the panic index continues to rise and safe assets such as bonds are being sought after, several economists interviewed by Caijing said that under the threat of the epidemic, loose monetary policy is likely to be the dominant theme in the economies. 'for the last decade, people have been trained to buy on the cheap because it works, ' Jeffrey Young told CAIJING. The stock market tumbled, the Fed eased, and if the epidemic became such that everyone had to stay home, how would lowering interest rates help?

So this "low" is different from the "bargain-hunting" investors have become accustomed to in bull markets over the past decade, according to Jeffery Young.

On Feb. 25, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention acknowledged that efforts were underway to provide state and local laboratories with new versions of the new coronavirus test kits, some of which were flawed. There are currently 57 confirmed cases in the United States, with only 426 people tested, not including citizens returning on evacuation flights.

Earlier, on Feb. 25, U.S. health and Human Services Secretary Azas led officials in a closed door briefing to members of Congress on the development of the new pneumonia in the United States. Shelby, chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee, told reporters after the closed door meeting that as things stand, $2.5 billion may not be enough to deal with the outbreak.

At the same time, a growing number of companies are worried about future earnings prospects, and some economists have cut their growth forecasts for the quarter, particularly in Asia.

Some in the market believe that the new crown pneumonia epidemic may be the end of this operation. With U.S. stocks at all-time highs, there is potential for further declines as it remains unclear when the new crown will disappear.

The U.S. economy is in good shape, and the administration has contained the COVID-19 outbreak, Kudlow, the White House's chief economic adviser, said Monday, as stock markets tumbled as the disease spread around the world. He urged everyone "not to panic" . "Our economy is in good shape, " he said. "The virus won't last. We've got it under control. I'm not going to say it's watertight, but these measures are very close to watertight. The United States is doing very well. " He added: Although the outbreak is a "human tragedy" , it may not be an "economic tragedy" in his view.

Jeffery young believes the Fed and treasury will have to resort to more "permissive" tools, like a series of measures by the Chinese government against banks, and important normalisation indicators to stabilise the market, the latest data from China's major industrial provinces such as Guangdong and Zhejiang are in good shape. The hope for a sustained upturn is that either the epidemic in China stabilises or the rest of the world moves quickly.
